snippet.textDisplay:
Some Amendments were proposed with drop dead dates. The only such Amendment I know of was #20. Section 6. Dead unless ratified within "seven years from the date of its submission."


This was not on the ERA, but Congress passed a law to add a date.  As that's a simple majority law, then it can be undone with just a law change, not a full Amendment process repeated.


Also, there is no process in the Constitution to "unratify" an Amendment.  In fact, my spell check tells me that's not even a word.  Once ratified, it can't be undone.  Otherwise, you could repeal the 2nd Amendment by getting 4 of the original states to unratify the 2nd Amendment.  Try that and see what the Conservatives suddenly say about unratifying Amendments.


Also, more coverage should be given to the anti-ERA groups.  Effectively it's funded by religion.  Oppressive religious factions worried that an ERA will be cited to justify legal abortions.  The ERA will be opposed by church money because abortion is still a primary issue for them.

Also, there is no process in the Constitution to "unratify" an Amendment.  In fact, my spell check tells me that's not even a word.  Once ratified, it can't be undone.  Otherwise, you could repeal the 2nd Amendment by getting 4 of the original states to unratify the 2nd Amendment.  Try that and see what the Conservatives suddenly say about unratifying Amendments.


Also, more coverage should be given to the anti-ERA groups.  Effectively it's funded by religion.  Oppressive religious factions worried that an ERA will be cited to justify legal abortions.  The ERA will be opposed by church money because abortion is still a primary issue for them.
